==English==

===Etymology===
Spokesmen for the Royal Society of London first coined the expression “brain drain” to describe the outflow of scientists and technologists to the United States and Canada in the early 1950s.

===Pronunciation===
{{wikipedia}}
* {{enPR|brānʹ-drān}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{def|The [[migration]] of [[educated]] or [[talented]] people from less economically [[advanced]] areas to more economically advanced areas, especially to large cities or richer countries.}}
